<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-10-16">
  <title>Resources for 10/16</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use your understanding of exponential functions to solve application problems (e.g. interest rate [including compound interest] &amp; radioactive decay).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Describe the end behavior of the function <m>f(x) = ab^x</m> for different values of <m>b</m> (i.e. what happens to the function as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m> or <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain why a vertical translation (and perhaps reflection) of an exponential function is appropriate for the temperature of an object over time.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given appropriate information about the temperature of an object and its environment, construct the formula for a function that models the temperature of the object.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-applications-exponential-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Applications of Exponential Functions (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>applications for exponential functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="IZzOgiYB4o4" />

    <example>
      <title>Exponential Applications</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following application problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose we invest money in an account with a fixed annual interest rate.  After two years, we have $250 and after five years we have $400.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the amount <m>A(t)</m> that is in the account after <m>t</m> years.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the interest rate on the account?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    How much money did we start out with?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose we own something that loses a fixed percentage of its value each year.  After 3 years, it is worth $300, and after 7 years, it is worth $200.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the value <m>V(t)</m> that the item is worth after <m>t</m> years.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the annual percentage that the value drops?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What was it worth at the beginning?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-exponential-end-behavior">
    <title>Video &amp; End Behavior of Exponential Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>end behavior of exponential functions</em> to help you understand the temperature models in the activities for the next video. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="IZzOgiYB4o4" />

    <example>
      <title>End Behavior of Exponential Functions (Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        These problems are to help you understand the end behavior of exponential functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>f(x)=3^x</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Look at <m>f(1)</m>, <m>f(2)</m>, <m>f(3)</m>, <m>f(4)</m>, and <m>f(5)</m>.  What is happening to the outputs of the function as the inputs get bigger?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets really big?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets really negative?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>f(x)=\left( \frac25 \right)^x</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Look at <m>f(1)</m>, <m>f(2)</m>, <m>f(3)</m>, <m>f(4)</m>, and <m>f(5)</m>.  What is happening to the outputs of the function as the inputs get bigger?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets really big?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets really negative?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>f(x)=a \cdot b^x</m>.  What happens to <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets really big or really negative?  Your answers will depend on the values of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose we want to use the function <m>f(x)=2 \cdot \left( \frac13 \right)^x</m> to model a phenomenon, but we need a function that gets close to 20 as <m>x</m> gets really big.  How can we adjust <m>f(x)</m> to make this happen?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-temperature-model">
    <title>Video &amp; Modeling Temperature with Exponential Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on using exponential functions to <em>model temperature</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="IZzOgiYB4o4" />

    <example>
      <title>Modeling Temperature with Exponential Functions</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following temperature problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              You bring a cup of cold water into a <m>68^\circ</m> room.  Initially, the water is <m>40^\circ</m>.  After 5 minutes, the water is <m>50^\circ</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If <m>W(t)</m> is the temperature of the water at time <m>t</m>, find a formula for <m>W(t)</m>.  Use the model <m>W(t)=a \cdot b^t+c</m> for appropriate constants <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>. Hint: Determine <m>c</m> first.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What will the temperature of the water be after 10 minutes?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              After dinner, you put your leftovers in the refrigerator, which is <m>38^\circ</m>.  Before you store the food in the refrigerator, it is room temperature, which is <m>68^\circ</m>.  After 30 minutes, the food temperature is down to <m>55^\circ</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If <m>L(t)</m> is the temperature of the leftovers at time <m>t</m>, find a formula for <m>L(t)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What will the temperature of the leftovers be after 75 minutes?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

